    answer: "**Viewport Meta Tag:**\nControls how a webpage is displayed on mobile devices by setting the viewport dimensions and scaling.\n\n**Basic Syntax:**\n```html\n<meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0\">\n```\n\n**Attributes:**\n• `width` - Viewport width (`device-width` or specific pixels)\n• `initial-scale` - Initial zoom level (1.0 = 100%)\n• `minimum-scale` - Minimum zoom level\n• `maximum-scale` - Maximum zoom level\n• `user-scalable` - Whether user can zoom (`yes` or `no`)\n• `viewport-fit` - For notched devices (`auto`, `cover`, `contain`)\n\n**Common Configurations:**\n```html\n<!-- Standard responsive setup -->\n<meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0\">\n\n<!-- Disable zooming (use carefully for accessibility) -->\n<meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0, user-scalable=no\">\n\n<!-- For full-screen apps -->\n<meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0, viewport-fit=cover\">\n```\n\n**Why It's Important:**\n• Without it, mobile browsers render pages at desktop width (typically 980px)\n• Enables responsive web design\n• Controls zoom behavior for accessibility\n\n**Impact on Responsive Design:**\n```css\n/* Works with viewport meta tag */\n@media (max-width: 768px) {\n    .container {\n        width: 100%;\n    }\n}\n```",
