    category: "css",
    question: "What are different positions in CSS?",
    answer: "**CSS Position Property:**\nDefines how an element is positioned in the document.\n\n**1. Static (default):**\n```css\nposition: static;\n```\n• Normal document flow\n• Not affected by top, right, bottom, left\n• Default positioning\n\n**2. Relative:**\n```css\nposition: relative;\ntop: 20px;\nleft: 30px;\n```\n• Relative to its normal position\n• Other elements not affected\n• Creates positioning context for absolute children\n\n**3. Absolute:**\n```css\nposition: absolute;\ntop: 0;\nright: 0;\n```\n• Removed from normal flow\n• Positioned relative to nearest positioned ancestor\n• If none, relative to viewport\n• Other elements behave as if it doesn't exist\n\n**4. Fixed:**\n```css\nposition: fixed;\ntop: 0;\nleft: 0;\n```\n• Removed from normal flow\n• Positioned relative to viewport\n• Stays fixed during scrolling\n• Used for headers, footers, modals\n\n**5. Sticky:**\n```css\nposition: sticky;\ntop: 0;\n```\n• Hybrid of relative and fixed\n• Behaves as relative until scroll threshold\n• Then becomes fixed\n• Used for sticky headers\n\n**Example:**\n```html\n<style>\n    .parent {\n        position: relative;\n        height: 300px;\n    }\n    \n    .absolute-child {\n        position: absolute;\n        bottom: 0;\n        right: 0;\n    }\n    \n    .fixed-element {\n        position: fixed;\n        bottom: 20px;\n        right: 20px;\n    }\n    \n    .sticky-header {\n        position: sticky;\n        top: 0;\n        background: white;\n    }\n</style>\n```\n\n**Z-index:**\n```css\n/* Controls stacking order */\nz-index: 10; /* Only works on positioned elements */\n```",
